Path: Creating Your Own Errors
Content:
Using the 
[link: metadata.md] metadata
 information, you can create your own custom error messages. Error messages are built of multiple parts:
The title of the error
The label of error message, which includes both the text of the label and the span to underline
You can use the 
[link: /commands/docs/error_make.md] ``error make``
 command to create your own error messages. For example, let's say you had your own command called 
``my-command``
 and you wanted to give an error back to the caller about something wrong with a parameter that was passed in.
First, you can take the span of where the argument is coming from:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let span = (metadata $x).span;

```
Next, you can create an error using the 
[link: /commands/docs/error_make.md] ``error make``
 command. This command takes in a record that describes the error to create:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
error make {msg: "this is fishy", label: {text: "fish right here", span: $span } }

```
Together with your custom command, it might look like this:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
def my-command [x] {
    let span = (metadata $x).span;
    error make {
        msg: "this is fishy",
        label: {
            text: "fish right here",
            span: $span
        }
    }
}

```
When called with a value, we'll now see an error message returned:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
my-command 100
# => Error:
# =>   Г— this is fishy
# =>    в•­в”Ђ[entry #5:1:1]
# =>  1 в”‚ my-command 100
# =>    В·            в”Ђв”¬в”Ђ
# =>    В·             в•°в”Ђв”Ђ fish right here
# =>    в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
